Here, however, come in other considerations ; the analy- tical process soon claims assistance from the syn— thetical. The desire for system—for order in the mass of evidence examined, in the various objects which have been subjected to analysis—the dis- crimination of principles only half separated from a perplexing substratum of facts; these all lead the mind on to philosophica] considerations and to its severest labour. The great desire is for simplicity and for a proper adjustment and sub- ordination of principles 3 the mind begins to see that in all beauty and grandeur of conception the element of simplicity is paramount.
